Oh My Goodness, Oh My Damn is a viral video remix of a Daym Drops YouTube food review that was popularized via lip dubs on TikTok. The original song was made by the Gregory Brothers on their autotune YouTube channel Schmoyoho in 2012 and features a remix of a video from the food review channel Daym Drops reviewing Five Guys burgers and fries. The chorus of the song, âOh my goodness, oh my damn, oh my goodness, theyâre going ham,â migrated to TikTok on its 10th anniversary in 2022 and became a sound TikTokers use to express their surprise and enjoyment of someone or something âgoing ham.â 

ORIGIN
On April 26th, 2012, the YouTube food review channel Daym Drops posted a video titled, âFive Guys Burgers and Fries Review.â The post gathered over 11 million views and 200,000 likes in roughly 10 years. On August 15th, the YouTube channel Schmoyoho then uploaded a video remixing the clip into a song, titled âOH MY DAYUM ft. @Daym Drops,â gathering over 44 million views and 600,000 likes in roughly 10 years. SPREAD
On January 30th, 2020, TikToker @haileythebaby posted a video using a snippet from the song and gathered over 900,000 views and over 64,000 likes in nearly two and a half years. On August 24th, 2022, TikToker @nillsis reuploaded the 2012 Schmoyoho remix alongside a text overlay that read, âThis Masterpiece Just Turned 10 Years Old.â The post gathered over 3.3 million plays and over 300,000 likes in nearly three weeks, spreading on the platform over the following month as other TikTokers began using it in lip-dub skits.

Aerials of Los Angeles from 1923, as photographed by Captain A.W. Stevens for the US Navy. Seeing all of these together, knowing that they were likely taken within days or hours of each other, is as close of an experience as I have ever had to traveling through time. 

Photos: 

â¢ 1. Bernheimer Estate & Gardens, now Yamashiro. The Lane Mansion (Magic Castle) is visible at bottom.

â¢ 2. The Goodyear Rubber Company, at 6701 S. Central Ave. Looking southwest here, so that's Gage below the plant, w/ McKinley, Stanford, and Avalon to the right. 

â¢ 3. Westlake Park, now Macarthur, with 6th St. to the left and 7th to the right. The bridge extending Wilshire over the lake was added in 1934.

â¢ 4. Pickford-Fairbanks Studios, on Santa Monica Blvd. at Formosa, with film sets for "The Thief of Baghdad.â Today, this is âThe Lot.â

â¢ 5. Salt Lake Oil Field, long before The Grove, Park La Brea, the Original Farmers Market, & Television City were built on top. Corner of Wilshire & Fairfax at bottom left, and you can just make out 3rd street cutting through oilfield. Derricks stretching past La Brea & Highland, all the way to Vine.

â¢ 6. Now Paramount, this was FBO Studios before they became RKO. Gower runs across the bottom, intersecting a tree-lined Melrose on the right. Hollywood Forever Cemetery on the left.

â¢ 7. The Southern Pacific Rail Depot, between Central & Alameda, stretching from 4th to 6th. Everything below is Skid Row, while everything above is now the Arts District. Depot is gone, but lots still standing here, incl. the LA Cold Storage Building, center left.

â¢ 8. Main channel of the Los Angeles Harbor, as fog obscures a densely-populated San Pedro to the right. Center left, you can make out the Japanese fishing village on Terminal Island that was razed during internment. 

â¢ 9. Colorado Street Bridge in Pasadena, with the horseshoe-shaped Rose Bowl Stadium at the top (south end was added in 1928). Vista del Arroyo Hotel at lower right when it was two-story bungalows. Bell-tower not added until 1930.

â¢ 10. The newly-completed Memorial Coliseum, still decorated for the Motion Picture Exposition from Wednesdayâs post.

Rover, obscure early LA #punk teen scenester, Masque denizen & nowadays a Las Vegas mom of 10 children, as captured ca. '77-'78 at the Atomic Cafe, in the Little Tokyo district of LA, in a photo provided to me by artist & activist @regi_mentle_ , a friend of hers back in the day & an active participant in the early LA/SF punk scene (a photo also used as the back cover of The Klan "Pushin' Too Hard" b/w "Cover Girls" 1980 single by Posh Boy).

Rover is one of those girls who, according to #alicebag : "added life and color to the early punk scene and made it so very interesting. She also received one of the first wounds (6 stitches in the scalp) in the "us against them" skirmishes that seem to occur whenever people are afraid or intolerant of those who look different from them. It's hard to imagine a time and place when having short, crazy-colored hair could provoke a violent reaction from a stranger, but that was what it was like in the 70s."

Being badly teased in school in So Cal just for being pale white, in '77 she was a 16-year-old who ended up actually living in the Masque, the Hollywood multi-roomed labyrinth, a club and a meeting spot that soon became the center of the universe to many punks, misfits, outsiders, degenerates and the nascent punk scene that had began bubbling up around '76, with groups like #thescreamers , #thegerms , #theweirdos , #thezeros , #thebags & the Go-Goâs, who she also roadied for.

As she recalls. "I walked into my very first show [a #dickies show at the Whiskey, Dec. '77] and knew I had finally found my home planet!!!! Remember the Twilight Zone episode with Elly May Clampett? She was laying in a hospital bed with bandages covering her face, consumed with self hatred & confusion because she was born so ugly that she couldn't fit in with society. The bandages came off & all had failed. Then it's revealed that she is really beautiful in a world of ugly & has to go live in a community with others like herself. That's exactly how I felt when I walked into the Whisky that night. Everyone was pale & it was ok."
